                    </div>
                    <span>This is a highly interesting history of the emergence of Lincoln's great rhetorical career during the civil war, starting with his railroad tour on the way to Washington after his election. Tracing the particulars and varied drafts of these gestating classics, the author puts each of the classic speeches in its context, especially the Gettesburg Address. The resulting fine-grain context for Lincoln's great masterpieces of eloquence is highly enjoyable and highlights the tenous edge they gave to his threatened passage as president through the trials of the Civil War. </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">The self-taught communicator</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
